1
00:00:01,768 --> 00:00:26,274
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hato samma-sambhodassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hato samma-sambhodassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hato samma-sambhodassa

2
00:00:27,233 --> 00:00:34,963
Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble and Fully Self-Awakened One.

3
00:00:34,984 --> 00:00:41,953
So I've chosen these two Dhammapada verses, 152 and 153.

4
00:00:43,956 --> 00:00:46,338
I shall do my little chanting.

5
00:00:47,128 --> 00:01:05,340
Sūdāsāṁ vājaṁ anyāsāṁ āttanopana-dhūdhu-sāṁ pārāsāṁ hiṣo ājjāni opunāti yathā-bhūsāṁ āttanopana-cādeiti kāliṁ vākita-vāsato

6
00:01:06,620 --> 00:01:29,403
And the translation, I'll do the one and then we'll do the little story that comes with it.

7
00:01:29,423 --> 00:01:35,849
So the first one is, it's easy to see the fault of others, but hard to see one's own.

8
00:01:37,028 --> 00:01:47,486
One sifts out the faults of others like chaff, but conceals one's own as a cheat, conceals a bad throw of the dice.

9
00:01:50,552 --> 00:01:55,480
The commentary, a little story.

10
00:01:55,500 --> 00:02:00,588
In the town of Badia there lived a rich man called Mendica.

11
00:02:01,192 --> 00:02:07,358
When the Buddha arrived at Baddhya, he realized that Mendaka and his whole family were able to understand the Dharma.

12
00:02:08,340 --> 00:02:17,710
He explained the teaching to them, and after hearing the Dharma from him, Mendaka, his wife, son, daughter-in-law and servant all attained first level of attainment.

13
00:02:18,751 --> 00:02:19,531
It was quick, wasn't it?

14
00:02:22,555 --> 00:02:30,002
Mendaka related how many ascetic teachers spoke ill of the Buddha and tried to dissuade Mendaka from seeing him.

15
00:02:30,825 --> 00:02:38,296
The Buddha explained by this verse that it is only very natural to see others' faults and not to see one's own.

16
00:02:40,099 --> 00:02:44,467
The Buddha then revealed the past existences of Mendaka.

17
00:02:44,486 --> 00:02:49,014
He was always a rich man who donated many things to those seeking awakening.

18
00:02:50,195 --> 00:02:52,639
So that's a big hint.

19
00:02:56,064 --> 00:02:58,268
You have to take these things with a pinch of salt, you know.

20
00:03:00,002 --> 00:03:06,289
So that's really about finding fault with others, not seeing one's own faults.

21
00:03:06,610 --> 00:03:07,371
That's the problem.

22
00:03:07,390 --> 00:03:10,334
I think we all do that to some extent.

23
00:03:12,515 --> 00:03:14,758
Now the next verse, much the same.

24
00:03:15,079 --> 00:03:25,469
If one focuses on others' faults and constantly takes offense, one's own toxins flourish and one is far from their destruction.

25
00:03:26,429 --> 00:03:43,037
Now here, Jill Fronsdale has translated the word asawa as toxins, but it's a particular word, it's a group of three, sometimes four, often translated as the taints or the cankers.

26
00:03:43,793 --> 00:04:01,599
and it includes sense desire as a leading to attachment, the desire to become eternally, to be yourself eternally, to be a person eternally, and ignorance or delusion.

27
00:04:02,241 --> 00:04:08,450
But sometimes you get this wrong view added to it, which seems to me just an extension of

28
00:04:09,223 --> 00:04:29,595
ignorance this ignorance avijja is often also uh talked about as moha which is delusion so it's sort of and of course that that will manifest in the way we think and how we understand things so um that was probably a later edition or a clarification

29
00:04:31,211 --> 00:04:37,076
So the commentary on that one is, there was a monk named Ujjana Sanyi.

30
00:04:37,579 --> 00:04:39,990
He was always finding faults with others.

31
00:04:40,442 --> 00:04:44,107
It's fairly easy to get angry in speaking ill of people.

32
00:04:44,127 --> 00:04:46,509
When the Buddha found out, he spoke this verse.

33
00:04:47,271 --> 00:04:50,454
He also added that sometimes finding faults with others is good.

34
00:04:50,815 --> 00:04:57,584
When we see someone misbehave and we try to teach that person good ways, then it's worthy of praise.

35
00:04:58,324 --> 00:05:09,858
But if we do it out of spite or malice, then we won't be able to achieve concentration, and therefore we get further and further away from awakening.

36
00:05:11,273 --> 00:05:14,577
Why would spite and malice stop us from achieving concentration?

37
00:05:17,182 --> 00:05:19,766
Well, the understanding is, of course, that it becomes a hindrance.

38
00:05:19,846 --> 00:05:21,548
It's always there in the back of our minds.

39
00:05:22,069 --> 00:05:30,041
It'll either replay itself, doing the same old thing in our fantasies, or we'll end up feeling guilty and horrible.

40
00:05:31,709 --> 00:05:35,718
So this one is really about hypocrites, I suppose.

41
00:05:35,918 --> 00:05:41,269
And of course, what came to mind was the sayings of Jesus.

42
00:05:41,589 --> 00:05:45,177
So in Matthew 7, verse 5,

43
00:05:46,288 --> 00:05:47,170
He's very abrupt.

44
00:05:47,713 --> 00:06:01,867
He was said to have spoken directly, thou hypocrite, thou cast out the beam out of thine own eye, and then shalt thou see clearly to cast out the mote out of thy brother's eye.

45
00:06:01,848 --> 00:06:03,031
So that's telling you.

46
00:06:03,853 --> 00:06:07,521
In Luke chapter 642, it's a bit more gentle.

47
00:06:08,384 --> 00:06:19,350
And how are you able to say to your brother, brother, permit, I may take out the speck in your eye yourself, not beholding the log in your own.

48
00:06:21,305 --> 00:06:32,077
The Buddha too, he asked people not to criticize young monks so much because it would take away their confidence.

49
00:06:32,278 --> 00:06:33,338
It discourages you.

50
00:06:35,601 --> 00:06:38,865
So just one or two questions to reflect upon.

51
00:06:39,125 --> 00:06:44,612
What is the effect on us when somebody criticizes us?

52
00:06:45,975 --> 00:06:50,399
I think we feel a certain anger, a certain resentment.

53
00:06:50,887 --> 00:06:53,009
You know, it's a bit infra dig and all that.

54
00:06:53,990 --> 00:07:12,637
So when we criticize somebody, it's always best to remind ourselves that their reaction is not going to be very pleasant unless somehow we can put it in a way that doesn't sound as though we are criticizing them.

55
00:07:12,658 --> 00:07:15,661
I remember

56
00:07:17,514 --> 00:07:44,333
once somebody i was a friend and he said to me just out of the blue he said you're jealous of me you see now actually it's not as though i don't suffer from jealousy this is going back now before i was a monk but i wasn't jealous of him anyway we were standing there and another friend came up and started praising my new jacket and when i turned this man was brimming with jealousy

57
00:07:44,447 --> 00:07:50,476
So often we criticize in others what we ourselves are not aware of.

58
00:07:50,557 --> 00:07:53,822
That's an old understanding, isn't it?

59
00:07:57,387 --> 00:08:08,062
But also I think sometimes we criticize others because we are caught up in our own understanding of how to behave.

60
00:08:08,584 --> 00:08:12,108
I'm just thinking of people coming late to meditation.

61
00:08:12,173 --> 00:08:17,399
So most people would get slightly angry with that, a bit miffed.

62
00:08:17,439 --> 00:08:21,464
Somebody's coming in constantly two, five minutes late, you know.

63
00:08:22,685 --> 00:08:25,449
And of course that would be justified.

64
00:08:25,470 --> 00:08:26,911
They shouldn't do that, you see.

65
00:08:28,374 --> 00:08:37,184
But then I think reflecting on the many times we've been late and upset people, it just does, it sort of understands, it undermines that sort of attitude.

66
00:08:40,236 --> 00:08:48,614
I think also there are times when we criticize somebody because we have a particular standard.

67
00:08:48,734 --> 00:08:57,350
So for instance, talking about punctuality, if we tend to be very punctual, we tend to be critical of somebody who isn't.

68
00:08:57,701 --> 00:09:02,067
And somehow there's an overlay.

69
00:09:02,148 --> 00:09:13,844
I mean, you might be a little miffed that somebody's come late, but if you're over-angry, then that suggests a certain pride, a certain holding on to one's opinions.

70
00:09:14,884 --> 00:09:16,407
It's got to be a bit easy with people.

71
00:09:18,309 --> 00:09:19,030
You've got to choose.

72
00:09:19,091 --> 00:09:24,258
The Buddha talks about, you know, when you're going to say something to somebody, that isn't going to be pleasant.

73
00:09:24,899 --> 00:09:27,101
You have to choose the right time, you know.

74
00:09:27,571 --> 00:09:53,679
don't you don't want to choose it just when they're at the peak of happiness you know and it has to be truthful you know and spoken gently and of course to know it's beneficial so that's important so if somebody comes late you might i mean sometimes i i do this to people who come late here you see i might say to them do you think uh you think you're coming late upsets the other meditators

75
00:09:57,371 --> 00:09:59,875
Perhaps sometimes I appeal to them.

76
00:09:59,894 --> 00:10:01,655
I'd be really pleased if you came early.

77
00:10:04,099 --> 00:10:13,528
So there are ways in which you can, shall we say, suggest, maybe without saying, you know, you shouldn't, you know, the bell goes, you should be here on time.

78
00:10:15,830 --> 00:10:17,552
Anyway, I'm too small to act like that.

79
00:10:17,831 --> 00:10:18,712
I'll get beaten up.

80
00:10:22,537 --> 00:10:27,361
Now, I did get slightly sidetracked here because I got into this,

81
00:10:27,663 --> 00:10:33,110
in a critic, looking at the beam in our own eye, the log in our own eye.

82
00:10:35,354 --> 00:10:48,793
And it sort of reminded me of Freud's superego and all that, where you've got this ethical component, you know, damning you and talking to how terrible you are.

83
00:10:50,106 --> 00:11:00,822
But I think we have to, you know, presuming that we can distinguish between constructive self-criticism and what is destructive.

84
00:11:00,842 --> 00:11:07,874
Obviously, it's important for us to be able to have a clear view of our shortcomings.

85
00:11:08,134 --> 00:11:09,014
That's not a problem.

86
00:11:09,676 --> 00:11:15,404
But I think often our inner critic, as they say, is really a bit over the top sometimes.

87
00:11:16,650 --> 00:11:24,682
And as I say, it produces a sense of inadequacy, shame, defeat, you know, all those low self-esteem, depression.

88
00:11:26,965 --> 00:11:31,951
We sometimes sort of absorb our abuser's language, you know, in times.

89
00:11:32,652 --> 00:11:41,724
I was thinking of a point where my father, I'd forgotten something.

90
00:11:43,826 --> 00:11:45,349
Oh, I've lost my page here, just a minute.

91
00:11:45,609 --> 00:11:46,269
What's happened there?

92
00:11:48,341 --> 00:12:08,663
here we are uh my father i'd forgotten something and my father said um forget means don't care now i you know i i you know and i was saying to myself no it doesn't not but in those days you didn't answer back you know you've got a smack on the head you know so i had to swallow that to forget these don't care

93
00:12:09,283 --> 00:12:16,432
Now, later on, of course, I began to realize, yeah, you know, if you care for something, you tend not to forget it.

94
00:12:17,092 --> 00:12:21,038
I mean, you don't forget the plane time that you're going to take when you go on holiday.

95
00:12:22,158 --> 00:12:25,423
And you don't forget meeting a friend for a cup of tea or something.

96
00:12:27,125 --> 00:12:36,134
So it's really when we don't want to forget something, if we make it important to ourselves, then we don't.

97
00:12:36,351 --> 00:12:43,679
Now the only exception to that is when you get old like me and then you get what you call senior moments.

98
00:12:44,020 --> 00:12:47,945
It doesn't matter how much you remind yourself, you just forget.

99
00:12:47,985 --> 00:12:52,470
Anyway, I came across...

100
00:12:57,054 --> 00:12:59,337
I'm going to share the screen with you.

101
00:13:11,738 --> 00:13:16,842
So this is a compilation by Jay Early and Bonnie Weiss.

102
00:13:18,004 --> 00:13:21,846
One is a psychologist and Bonnie is a psychotherapist.

103
00:13:22,807 --> 00:13:25,610
And they've come up with these seven types of inner critics.

104
00:13:25,770 --> 00:13:26,831
I thought, well, that's interesting.

105
00:13:27,753 --> 00:13:40,024
I thought we'd just read through these and then afterwards we can all have a little discussion as to which one we're guilty of.

106
00:13:41,388 --> 00:13:44,331
So the first one is this perfectionist, perfectionism.

107
00:13:45,211 --> 00:13:48,134
The critic tries to get you to do things perfectly.

108
00:13:48,634 --> 00:13:59,102
It sets high standard for things you produce and has difficulty saying something is complete and letting it go out to represent your best work.

109
00:13:59,123 --> 00:14:04,148
Tries to make sure that you fit in and that you will not be judged or rejected.

110
00:14:04,408 --> 00:14:10,432
And its expectations probably reflect those of people who've been important to you in the past.

111
00:14:11,003 --> 00:14:25,840
and uh that sort of critic um when it comes i think you you have to recognize it you know it's like you're doing vipassana and you you record you call it by its name now that's perfectionism and then you have to feel

112
00:14:26,191 --> 00:14:28,214
You have to feel the negativity of it.

113
00:14:28,955 --> 00:14:33,922
And then you have to remind yourself, a person cannot be perfect.

114
00:14:33,942 --> 00:14:34,964
It's just a fact.

115
00:14:35,004 --> 00:14:36,044
You can't be perfect.

116
00:14:36,686 --> 00:14:37,407
But you can.

117
00:14:37,967 --> 00:14:38,889
You can be excellent.

118
00:14:38,948 --> 00:14:41,172
You can do things as best as you can.

119
00:14:41,413 --> 00:14:43,134
And that's good enough.

120
00:14:43,154 --> 00:14:47,981
So in a sense, these inner critics, you have to actually acknowledge them.

121
00:14:48,342 --> 00:14:51,226
You have to feel what they're doing to you in your heart.

122
00:14:51,626 --> 00:14:53,429
I mean, they're all aversive.

123
00:14:53,849 --> 00:15:22,100
and and then when that passes you've got to find the opposite so here we have the inner controller so this critic tries to control your impulses eating drinking sexual activity and so on it's polarized with an indulger an addict who it fears can get out of control at any moment it tends to be harsh and shaming in an effort to protect you from yourself it is motivated

124
00:15:22,384 --> 00:15:27,192
to try and make you a good person, which is accepted and functions well in society.

125
00:15:27,712 --> 00:15:30,216
Now, in a sense, of course, part of that's good.

126
00:15:30,297 --> 00:15:38,168
I mean, we don't want to be overcome by habits such as overeating and things like that.

127
00:15:38,769 --> 00:15:47,403
But on the other hand, there's a sort of overlay of that, which can make life miserable for you.

128
00:15:48,384 --> 00:15:50,788
So this harsh and shaming, see?

129
00:15:51,815 --> 00:15:56,980
So again, I think it's a case of feeling it, naming it for what it is.

130
00:15:57,181 --> 00:15:59,104
That's the controller.

131
00:15:59,683 --> 00:16:03,089
And then just to sit with it till that aversion disappears.

132
00:16:04,149 --> 00:16:06,873
And then to talk to yourself kindly.

133
00:16:07,653 --> 00:16:14,261
Yes, the Buddha's word is restraint, to exercise restraint.

134
00:16:16,485 --> 00:16:18,269
Then we have the taskmaster.

135
00:16:18,308 --> 00:16:21,714
So the critic wants you to work hard and be successful.

136
00:16:21,833 --> 00:16:28,865
And it fears that you may be mediocre or lazy and will be judged as a failure if it does not push you to keep going.

137
00:16:29,986 --> 00:16:36,317
It's pushing often activates a procrastinator, a rebel that fights against its harsh dictate.

138
00:16:36,738 --> 00:16:40,923
So here we have a real contradictory mental state.

139
00:16:42,692 --> 00:17:09,425
and i think again it's the same thing you know to to actually feel that and hear what it's saying you know and to name it and then and then and then what one other thing we can do is to have a conversation with it you know that you're not lazy insist that you're not lazy by any means let me just knock this up a bit so i can i'm hoping i can scroll this

140
00:17:12,156 --> 00:17:27,094
yes okay uh the next one is the uh is the underminer there we are so the critic tries to undermine your self-confidence and self-esteem so that you won't take risks

141
00:17:27,664 --> 00:17:38,755
It makes direct attacks on your self-worth so that you will be able to stay small and not take chances where you could be hurt or rejected.

142
00:17:38,775 --> 00:17:44,240
It's afraid of your being too big, too visible, and not being able to tolerate judgment or failure.

143
00:17:44,621 --> 00:17:49,444
So this seems to center on this self-confidence, self-esteem.

144
00:17:50,185 --> 00:17:55,730
Fear of failure, that really can be such a destroyer of life.

145
00:17:56,182 --> 00:17:59,318
You don't do anything just in case you fail.

146
00:17:59,338 --> 00:18:03,038
That can be quite destructive.

147
00:18:04,029 --> 00:18:06,834
one has to take the measured risk.

148
00:18:06,854 --> 00:18:14,944
And in so doing, even failure becomes a success because then you know it's a learning process.

149
00:18:15,025 --> 00:18:21,273
But if you're always going to be afraid of failing, then you just don't risk anything.

150
00:18:21,334 --> 00:18:27,422
You just stay dead safe and you undermine your potential.

151
00:18:29,426 --> 00:18:31,530
So it's the same with the destroyer.

152
00:18:31,632 --> 00:18:35,400
So it makes pervasive attacks on your fundamental self-worth.

153
00:18:35,779 --> 00:18:43,015
It shames you and makes you feel inherently flawed and not entitled to basic understanding or respect.

154
00:18:43,035 --> 00:18:46,643
This most debilitating critic comes...

155
00:18:46,623 --> 00:19:15,211
comes from early life deprivation or trauma and it is motivated by belief that is safer not to exist my goodness so that's a if you're if there is that within us then that really has to be tackled that's not that's not a very good thing to have within us but again uh you know it's it is very much a case of naming it not being afraid of it turning towards it and really getting into the

156
00:19:15,866 --> 00:19:43,883
motivating moods the motivating um emotional states and to hold steady to be with that you know and to know that it passes and when it passes and we haven't indulged it it's actually being weakened all the time it's only a habit that's what it is just a habit and then of course to turn around upon ourselves and and say things that make us feel

157
00:19:45,060 --> 00:19:46,903
We are worthy.

158
00:19:48,976 --> 00:20:16,671
old guilt tripper well that's that's a regular one i think this critic is stuck in the past it's unable to forgive you for wrongs you've done or people you've hurt it is concerned about relationship and holds you to standards of behavior prescribed by your community culture and family tries to protect you from repeating past mistakes by making sure you never forget or feel free oh yeah guilt can be uh

159
00:20:18,035 --> 00:20:33,630
bit awful really always feeling that you know we we've done something terrible it can almost be an amorphous feeling which is all hangs around you know you are guilty you know you ought to be hanged and uh and that of course just messes your relationships up

160
00:20:36,917 --> 00:20:42,826
So again, much the same way, to feel the guilt, know it's delusive.

161
00:20:43,146 --> 00:20:47,374
Now here, of course, we have to be careful because there is proper guilt.

162
00:20:47,934 --> 00:20:58,150
I mean, if we do something wrong, which is plainly wrong, or if we know it's plainly wrong, then obviously we should feel guilty.

163
00:20:58,923 --> 00:21:00,464
and shameful.

164
00:21:01,266 --> 00:21:05,771
When it works at that level, the Buddha calls them the two guardians of society.

165
00:21:06,132 --> 00:21:07,653
That's tough for us to accept.

166
00:21:07,854 --> 00:21:10,798
We have such a downer on guilt and shame.

167
00:21:11,219 --> 00:21:17,547
But when they actually activate to correct our behavior, then they're doing their job.

168
00:21:18,107 --> 00:21:21,872
And once the behavior is corrected, there shouldn't be any more guilt and shame.

169
00:21:22,153 --> 00:21:23,934
That's the way it ought to work.

170
00:21:25,265 --> 00:21:28,671
And then it stays in the background as a lesson.

171
00:21:29,112 --> 00:21:35,983
And so it stops you doing the same thing again, the same wrong things again, because you remember, oh, when I do that, this is how I feel.

172
00:21:36,684 --> 00:21:43,678
But if it continues and continues, then it's become an obsessive mental state.

173
00:21:46,071 --> 00:21:47,933
And then finally the conformist.

174
00:21:48,035 --> 00:21:56,505
So the critic tries to get you to fit into a certain mode based on standards held by society, your culture or your family.

175
00:21:58,528 --> 00:22:07,219
It wants you to be liked and admired and to protect you from being abandoned, shamed or rejected.

176
00:22:07,239 --> 00:22:12,165
The conformist fears that the rebel or the free spirit in you would act in ways that are unacceptable.

177
00:22:12,445 --> 00:22:15,690
So it keeps you from being in touch with and expressing your true nature.

178
00:22:16,362 --> 00:22:24,213
So again, yes, I'm reminded actually of a monk who joined the order, of a man who joined the order.

179
00:22:24,954 --> 00:22:27,077
